 @MilesTraveler  A high divorce rate doesn't mean people are breaking up for less important reasons.
The rate of divorce has climbed in proportion to the lessening of the taboo on divorce. Social acceptance, not tweets, is the cause.
I didn't even need a search engine for that. It just popped into my head. Because it's fucking obvious.

 @aarondavis8943  So you think it's the natural state of humans to mostly divorce, and social acceptance of that had allowed it to happen? That would mean that marriages are objectively best describable as just temporary mating arrangements. If that's the case, why do people get married at all? Why take the vows? Is it just that social acceptance hasn't caught up to the reality that marriage is a sham? And if all that is true, then the people who are in happy lifelong marriages are actually doing something anathemistic to nature and have been for all of human history up to this point.

So we're left with two options — One: that marriage is an unnatural and socially enforced arrangement that has plagued humanity up until the past few decades. Or two: that you have a personal distate for marriage which you're projecting onto the situation.

It's likely that both are true to some extent. People definitely have been pressured to marry historically and divorce is usually looked down on. That doesn't mean that they only marry for social pressures or that every divorce is justified, though.

